# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: republic-of-ireland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] The **10th (Irish) Division**, was one of the first of Kitchener's New Army K1 Army Group divisions (formed from Kitchener's 'first hundred thousand' new volunteers), authorized on 21 August 1914, after the outbreak of the Great War.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] It included battalions from the various provinces of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] It was initially led by the Irish Lieutenant General Sir Bryan Mahon and fought at Gallipoli in 1915, Salonika, from 1915–1917, and Palestine from 1917–1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] It was the first of the Irish divisions to take to the field and was the most travelled of the Irish formations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] The division served as a formation of the United Kingdom's British Army during World War I.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] Formed in Ireland on 21 August 1914, the 10th Division was sent to Gallipoli where, as part of Lieutenant General Sir Frederick Stopford's IX Corps, at Suvla Bay on 7 August it participated in the Landing at Suvla Bay and the August offensive.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] Some battalions of the division were landed at Anzac and fought at Chunuk Bair.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] In September 1915, when the Suvla front became a stalemate, the division was moved to Salonika where it remained for almost two years and fought the Battle of Kosturino.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] The division moved to Egypt in September 1917 where it joined Lieutenant General Sir Philip Chetwode's XX Corps.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] It fought in the Third Battle of Gaza which succeeded in breaking the resistance of the Turkish defenders in southern Palestine.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] Heavy losses on the Western Front following Operation Michael, the great German spring offensive in 1918, resulted in the transfer of ten of the division's battalions from Palestine to France, their place being taken by Indian Army units.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] This left only one British battalion per brigade.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] The remainder of the division remained in Palestine until the end of the war with Turkey on 31 October 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/10th-irish-division-united-kingdom] On 12 November 1918 the division concentrated at Sarafand, ready for moving back to Egypt.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The **16th (Irish) Division** was an infantry division of the British Army, raised for service during World War I.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The division was a voluntary 'Service' formation of Lord Kitchener's New Armies, created in Ireland from the 'National Volunteers', initially in September 1914, after the outbreak of the Great War.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In December 1915, the division moved to France, joining the British Expeditionary Force (BEF), under the command of Irish Major General William Hickie, and spent the duration of the war in action on the Western Front.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Following enormous losses at the Somme, Passchendaele and Ypres, the 16th (Irish) Division required a substantial refit in England between June and August 1918, which involved the introduction of many non-Irish battalions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Moved by the fate of Belgium, a small and Catholic country, John Redmond had called on Irishmen to enlist "in defence of the highest principles of religion and morality and right".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] More Catholic Irish enlisted than Protestants.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The 16th Division began forming as part of the K2 Army Group towards the end of 1914 after Irish recruits in the early days of the war from England and Belfast first filled the ranks of the 10th (Irish) Division before being assigned to the 16th Division, formed around a core of National Volunteers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Initial training began in Ireland at Fermoy, Munster; recruits also trained at Buttevant.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The division moved to Aldershot in Hampshire, England for more intensive training in September 1915.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] After thirteen weeks, the division was deployed to Étaples in France, joining the British Expeditionary Force (BEF), then commanded by Field Marshal Sir John French, but later replaced by General Sir Douglas Haig.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] From there the division left on 18 December for that part of the front in the Loos salient, under the command of Irish Major General William Hickie, who had distinguished himself earlier in the war as a staff officer and brigade commander, and spent the rest of the war on the Western Front.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Until March 1916 the 16th Division was part of IV Corps, commanded by the staunch unionist, Lieutenant General Sir Henry Wilson.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Wilson, who had called the division "Johnnie Redmond's pets", inspected them over the course of a few days over Christmas 1915, noting that they "appear to be inferior" and that "at least 50p.c. are quite useless, old whiskey-sodden militiamen".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Hickie agreed that he had "a political Divn of riff raff Redmondites".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Wilson thought the 47th Brigade had "old officers, old & useless men, *very* bad musketry, rotten boots, and altogether a very poor show".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Wilson reported to his superior, General Sir Charles Monro (6 January) that the division, despite having been training since September–October 1914, would not be fit to serve in an active part of the line for six weeks.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Hickie was–in public–much more diplomatic and tactful and spoke of the pride which his new command gave him.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] At Loos, in January and February 1916, the division was introduced to trench warfare and suffered greatly in the Battle of Hulluch.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Personnel raided German trenches all through May and June.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In late July they were moved to the Somme Valley where they were intensively engaged in the Battle of the Somme.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Lieutenant General Hubert Gough, the British Fifth Army commander, had asked, at the end of 1915, for the division to be placed under his command, and had established the first corps school for the training of young officers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The 16th Division played an important part in capturing the towns of Guillemont and Ginchy, although they suffered massive casualties.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] During these successful actions between 1 and 10 September casualties amounted to 224 officers and 4,090 men; despite these very heavy losses the division gained a reputation as first-class shock troops.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Out of a total of 10,845 men, it had lost 3,491 on the Loos sector between January and the end of May 1916, including heavy casualties from bombardment and a gas attack at Hullach in April.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Bloodletting of this order was fatal to the division's character, for it had to be made good by drafts from England.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In early 1917, the division took a major part in the Battle of Messines alongside the 36th (Ulster) Division, adding to both their recognition and reputation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Their major actions ended in the summer of 1917 at the Battle of Passchendaele after, again, coming under the command of Gough and the Fifth Army.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] By mid August, the 16th had suffered over 4,200 casualties, the 36th almost 3,600, or more than 50% of their numbers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Haig, now a field marshal, was very critical of Gough for "playing the Irish card".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The 16th Division held an exposed position from early 1918 at Ronssoy where they suffered more heavy losses during the German Army's Spring Offensive in March and being practically wiped out in the retreat which followed Operation Michael.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] Haig wrote in his diary (22 March 1918) that the division was "said not to be so full of fight as the others.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In fact, certain Irish units did very badly and gave way immediately the enemy showed".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In fact the division's casualties were the highest of any BEF division at this time, and records of the German 18th and 50th Reserve Divisions show that the Irish fought hard.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The corps commander, Lieutenant General Walter Congreve, wrote "the real truth is that their reserve brigade did not fight at all and their right brigade very indifferently".
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The matter affected the debate over the introduction of conscription of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The remnants of the division were later transferred to XIX Corps of the Third Army.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The 16th helped to finally halt the German attack prior to the Battle of Hamel.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The decision was then made to break up the division, the three surviving Service battalions were posted to other formations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] On 14 June the division returned to England for reconstitution.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The Conscription Crisis of 1918 in Ireland meant that fewer Irish recruits could be raised so that the 16th Division which returned to France on 27 July contained five English battalions, two Scottish battalions and one Welsh battalion.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The only original battalion left was the 5th Royal Irish Fusiliers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The dispersion of the Irish battalions throughout the BEF in 1918, despite its practical considerations, appears to suggest that the Irish units were increasingly distrusted by the military authorities.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] The 47th Brigade was known as the "Nationalist Brigade" as the majority were men from Redmond's Irish Volunteers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In the French village of Guillemont there is a celtic cross memorial in remembrance of the division.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] In 2016 a centenery ceremony was held to commemorate the division's partipation in the Battle of the Somme.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] It was attended by representatives of both the British and Irish governments.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] At Wytschaete Cemetery, Belgium, there are two memorial stones facing opposite one another dedicated to the 36th Ulster Division and 16th Irish Division, in order to commemorate their fighting together during the Battle of Messines Ridge.
[src:republic-of-ireland/16th-irish-division] There is also a celtic cross memorial at the same location.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Literature of the 18th century refers to world literature produced during the years 1700–1799.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] European literature of the 18th century refers to literature (poetry, drama, satire, essays, and novels) produced in Europe during this period.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The 18th century saw the development of the modern novel as literary genre, in fact many candidates for the first novel in English date from this period, of which Daniel Defoe's 1719 *Robinson Crusoe* is probably the best known.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Subgenres of the novel during the 18th century were the epistolary novel, the sentimental novel, histories, the gothic novel and the libertine novel.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 18th century Europe started in the Age of Enlightenment and gradually moved towards Romanticism.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In the visual arts, it was the period of Neoclassicism.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The 18th century in Europe was the Age of Enlightenment, and literature explored themes of social upheaval, reversals of personal status, political satire, geographical exploration and the comparison between the supposed natural state of man and the supposed civilized state of man.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Translations of foreign-language works became ever-more ubiquitous in Europe in the 18th century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Works translated from French to English and vice versa were particularly common, but works written in nearly all major world languages, from Arabic to Greek, likewise proliferated.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In 1708, Simon Ockley translated Ibn Tufail's *Hayy ibn Yaqdhan* directly from Arabic to English for the first time, while Michael Wodhull was the first to translate all the extant writing of Euripides into English, with his work published in four volumes in 1782.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Translations in the eighteenth century were typically liberal and loose, as it was common for translators to alter the text to appeal more to their intended audience and to add their own original work to it.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] John Lockman, for example, described his French translations as "versions" to indicate the large changes he'd made to the original text.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Unclear labeling further complicated matters, resulting in complicated translation loops.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In some cases, works of fiction were translated from French to English and, later, from English back into French, with the second translator being unaware that the work they were translating was not the original.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Notable eighteenth-century translators from Asia included Sugita Genpaku, who translated the Dutch medical work *Kaitai Shinsho* into Japanese in 1774, making it among the first Western works to be translated in Japan.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1700: William Congreve's play *The Way of the World* premiered.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Although unsuccessful at the time, *The Way of the World* is a good example of the sophistication of theatrical thinking during this period, with complex subplots and characters intended as ironic parodies of common stereotypes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1703: Nicholas Rowe's domestic drama *The Fair Penitent*, an adaptation of Massinger and Field's *Fatal Dowry*, appeared; it would later be pronounced by Dr Johnson to be one of the most pleasing tragedies in the language.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1703 Sir Richard Steele's comedy *The Tender Husband* achieved some success.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1704: Jonathan Swift (Irish satirist) published *A Tale of a Tub* and *The Battle of the Books* and John Dennis published his *Grounds of Criticism in Poetry*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] *The Battle of the Books* begins with a reference to the use of a glass (which, in those days, would mean either a mirror or a magnifying glass) as a comparison to the use of satire.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Swift is, in this, very much the child of his age, thinking in terms of science and satire at one and the same time.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Swift often patterned his satire after Juvenal, the classical satirist.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] He was one of the first English novelists and also a political campaigner.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] His satirical writing springs from a body of liberal thought which produced not only books but also political pamphlets for public distribution.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Swift's writing represents the new, the different and the modern attempting to change the world by parodying the ancient and incumbent.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] *The Battle of the Books* is a short writing which demonstrates his position very neatly.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1706: *Dildoides: A Burlesque Poem* was published in London, attributed on its title page to Samuel Butler (an attribution rejected by modern scholarship) and sometimes credited to Sir Charles Sedley.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1707: Henry Fielding was born on 22 April.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1711: Alexander Pope began a career in literature with the publishing of his *An Essay on Criticism*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1712: French philosophical writer Jean Jacques Rousseau was born on 28 June and his countryman Denis Diderot was born the following year 1713 on 5 October.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1712 Pope published *The Rape of the Lock* and in 1713 *Windsor Forest*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1709: Samuel Johnson was born on 18 September in Lichfield, Staffordshire.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1717: Horace Walpole was born on 24 September.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Daniel Defoe was another political pamphleteer turned novelist like Jonathan Swift and was publishing in the early 18th century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In 1719, he published *Robinson Crusoe*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1719: Eliza Haywood published *Love in Excess*, an unusually sympathetic portrayal of a fallen woman.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1719: Alexander Smith was a biographer who published *A Complete History of the Lives and Robberies of the Most Notorious Highwaymen*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The book includes heavily fictionalised accounts of English criminals from the medieval period to the eighteenth century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1720: Daniel Defoe's *Captain Singleton* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1722: Daniel Defoe's *Moll Flanders* and *A Journal of the Plague Year* were published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1726: Jonathan Swift published *Gulliver's Travels*, one of the first novels in the genre of satire.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1728: John Gay wrote *The Beggar's Opera* which has increased in fame ever since.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] *The Beggar's Opera* began a new style in Opera, the "ballad opera" which brings the operatic form down to a more popular level and precedes the genre of comic operettas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1728 came the publication of *Cyclopaedia, or, A Universal Dictionary of Arts and Sciences* (folio, 2 vols.), an encyclopedia by Ephraim Chambers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The *Cyclopaedia* was one of the first general encyclopedias to be produced in English and was the main model for Diderot's *Encyclopédie* (published in France between 1751 and 1766).
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1729: Jonathan Swift published *A Modest Proposal*, a satirical suggestion that Irish families should sell their children as food.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Swift was, at this time, fully involved in political campaigning for the Irish.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1731: George Lillo's play *The London Merchant* was a success at the Theatre-Royal in Drury Lane.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] It was a new kind of play, a domestic tragedy, which approximates to what later came to be called a melodrama.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1738: Samuel Johnson published *London*, a poem in imitation of Juvenal’s Third Satire.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Like so many poets of the 18th century, Johnson sought to breathe new life into his favorite classical author Juvenal.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1740: Samuel Richardson's *Pamela, or Virtue Rewarded* was published and the Marquis de Sade was born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1744: Alexander Pope died, and in 1745 Jonathan Swift died.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1746: Tobias Smollett's first poem "*The Tears of Scotland*", about the Battle of Culloden, was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1748: John Cleland's *Memoirs of a Woman of Pleasure* (popularly known as *Fanny Hill*), arguably the first work of pornographic prose, was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1748, Samuel Richardson's *Clarissa; or, The History of a Young Lady* was published; finally, Tobias Smollett's first picaresque quasi-autobiographical novel *The Adventures of Roderick Random* was also published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1749: Henry Fielding's *The History of Tom Jones, a Foundling* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] His sister Sarah Fielding also published *The Governess*, the first full-length novel written for children.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1751: Thomas Gray wrote *Elegy Written in a Country Churchyard*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1751, Denis Diderot began the *Encyclopédie, ou dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Over the next three decades *Encyclopédie* attracted, alongside of those from Diderot, notable contributions from other notable intellectuals of the 18th century including Voltaire, Jean-Jacques Rousseau and Louis de Jaucourt.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1755: Samuel Johnson completed his influential *Dictionary of the English Language*, sometimes published as *Johnson's Dictionary*, and at the time a huge improvement on previously available dictionaries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] It was a daunting task that took nine years in all, two years of preparation and seven years of research and writing.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1760–1767: Laurence Sterne wrote *Tristram Shandy*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1764: Horace Walpole published *The Castle of Otranto* (initially under a pseudonym and claiming it to be a translation of an Italian work from 1529); the first gothic novel.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1766: Oliver Goldsmith's *The Vicar of Wakefield* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1770: William Wordsworth was born on 7 April.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1771: Tobias Smollett published his epistolatory novel, *The Expedition of Humphry Clinker* just three months before his death.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1773: Oliver Goldsmith's play *She Stoops to Conquer*, a farce, was performed in London.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1776: The United States Declaration of Independence was created and ratified.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1777: The play *The School for Scandal*, a comedy of manners by Richard Brinsley Sheridan, was first performed in Drury Lane.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1778: Frances Burney published *Evelina* anonymously.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1779–1781: Samuel Johnson wrote and published *Lives of the Most Eminent English Poets*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] This compilation contains short biographies of 52 influential poets (most of whom lived in the 18th century) along with critical appraisals of their works.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Most notable are Alexander Pope, John Dryden, John Milton, Jonathan Swift, and Joseph Addison.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1784: Samuel Johnson died on 13 December.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1785: William Cowper published *The Task*, a volume of poetry in blank verse.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1786: Robert Burns published *Poems Chiefly in the Scottish Dialect*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The mood of literature was swinging toward more interest in diverse ethnicity.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Beaumarchais' *The Marriage of Figaro* (*La Folle journée ou Le Mariage de Figaro*) was adapted into a comic opera composed by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, with libretto by Lorenzo da Ponte.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1789: James Fenimore Cooper was born on 15 September.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1789, *The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano*, one of the first slave narratives to have been widely read in historical times, was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1792: Percy Bysshe Shelley was born on 4 August.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1793: *Salisbury Plain* was published by William Wordsworth.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1794: Ann Radcliffe published her most famous Gothic novel, *The Mysteries of Udolpho*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1795: Samuel Taylor Coleridge met William Wordsworth and his sister Dorothy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The two men published a joint volume of poetry, *Lyrical Ballads* (1798), which became a central text of Romantic poetry.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1796: Matthew Lewis published his controversial anti-Catholic gothic novel *The Monk* and Charlotte Smith published her novel *Marchmont*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1796, Mary Hays published her outspoken novel *Memoirs of Emma Courtney*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] From 1704 to 1717, Antoine Galland published *One Thousand and One Nights* (also known as *The Arabian Nights* in English), based on Arabian folk tales.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] His version of the tales appeared in twelve volumes and exerted a huge influence on subsequent European literature and attitudes to the Islamic world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Galland's translation of the *Nights* was immensely popular throughout Europe, and later versions of the *Nights* were written by Galland's publisher using Galland's name without his consent.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In 1707, playwright Carlo Goldoni was born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] In 1729, Gotthold Ephraim Lessing was born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1752 *Micromégas*, a satirical short story by Voltaire, features space travellers visiting Earth.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] It is one of the first stories to feature several elements of what will later become known as science fiction.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Its publication at this time is also indicative of the trend toward scientific thinking that characterizes the Enlightenment.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1759 Voltaire's *Candide*/*Optimism* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] On November 10, Johann Christoph Friedrich von Schiller is born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1761 Jean Jacques Rousseau's *Julie, ou la nouvelle Héloïse* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1762 Jean Jacques Rousseau's *Émile* was published.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1767 September 8: August Wilhelm von Schlegel was born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1772 March 10: Karl Wilhelm Friedrich von Schlegel was born.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1774 Goethe wrote *The Sorrows of Young Werther*, a novel which approximately marks the beginning of the Romanticism movement in the arts and philosophy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] A transition thus began from the critical, science-inspired, Enlightenment writing to the romantic yearning for forces beyond the mundane and for foreign times and places to inspire the soul with passion and mystery.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Also in 1774, Alberto Fortis published his travel book *Viaggio in Dalmazia* ("Journey to Dalmatia") and started Morlachism.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1776 Ignacy Krasicki published the first novel in Polish, *The Adventures of Mr.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Two major contributors to Diderot's *Encyclopédie* died in the same year.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Voltaire, Rousseau and Diderot have all died within a period of a few years, and French philosophy had thus lost three of its greatest enlightened free thinkers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Rousseau's thoughts on the nobility of life in the wilds, facing nature as a naked savage, still had great force to influence the next generation as the Romantic movement gained momentum.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Beaumarchais wrote *The Marriage of Figaro*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] Maria and Harriet Falconar publish *Poems on Slavery*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] The anti-slavery movement was growing in power, and many poems and pamphlets were published on the subject.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1791 *Dream of the Red Chamber* was published for the first time in movable type format.
[src:republic-of-ireland/18th-century-in-literature] 1796 Denis Diderot's *Jacques le fataliste* was published posthumously.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish component of the 1918 United Kingdom general election took place on 14 December 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the final United Kingdom general election to be held throughout Ireland, as the next election would happen following Irish independence.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It is a key moment in modern Irish history, seeing the overwhelming defeat of the moderate nationalist Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP), which had dominated the Irish political landscape since the 1880s, and a landslide victory for the radical Sinn Féin party.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin had never previously stood in a general election, but had won six seats in by-elections in 1917–1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had vowed in its manifesto to establish an independent Irish Republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster, however, the Unionist Party was the most successful party.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the elections, Sinn Féin's elected members refused to attend the British Parliament in Westminster (London), and instead formed a parliament in Dublin, the First Dáil Éireann ("Assembly of Ireland"), which declared Irish independence as a republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish War of Independence was conducted under this revolutionary government which sought international recognition, and set about the process of state-building.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The other parties elected in the election were invited by Sinn Féin to join in creating the Dáil Éireann, but declined and took up their seats at Westminster.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 a system called plural voting was in place in both Britain and Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting was a practice whereby one person might be able to vote multiple times in an election.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Property and business owners could vote both in the constituency where their property lay and that in which they lived, if the two were different.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This system often resulted in one person being able to cast multiple votes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the newly formed Irish Free State this system was ended by the Electoral Act 1923 and was abolished in the UK by the Representation of the People Act 1948.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting remained in effect in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The 1918 election was held in the aftermath of World War I, the Easter Rising and the Conscription Crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the first general election to be held after the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was thus the first election in which women over the age of 30, and all men over the age of 21, could vote.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Previously, all women and most working-class men had been excluded from voting.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 the whole of Ireland was a part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and was represented in the British Parliament by 105 Members of Parliament (MPs).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Whereas in Great Britain most elected politicians were members of either the Liberal Party or the Conservative Party, from the early 1880s most Irish MPs were Irish nationalists, who sat together in the British House of Commons as the Irish Parliamentary Party.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP strove for Home Rule, that is, limited self-government for Ireland within the United Kingdom, and had been supported by most Irish people, especially the Catholic majority.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule was opposed by most Protestants in Ireland, who formed a majority of the population in parts of the northern province of Ulster but a minority in the rest of Ireland, and favoured maintenance of the Union with Great Britain (and were therefore called Unionists).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionists were supported by the Conservative Party, whereas from 1885 the Liberal Party was committed to enacting some form of Home Rule.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists eventually formed their own representation, first the Irish Unionist Party then the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule appeared to have been finally achieved with the passing of the Home Rule Act 1914.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the implementation of the Act was temporarily postponed with the outbreak of World War I due to determined Ulster Unionists' resistance to the Act.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As the war prolonged and with the failure to make any progress on the issue, the more radical Sinn Féin began to grow in strength.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin was founded by Arthur Griffith in 1905.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He believed that Irish nationalists should emulate the *Ausgleich* of Hungarian nationalists who, in the 19th century under Ferenc Deák, had chosen to boycott the imperial parliament in Vienna and unilaterally established their own legislature in Budapest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Griffith had favoured a peaceful solution based on 'dual monarchy' with Britain, that is two separate states with a single head of state and a limited central government to control matters of common concern only.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, by 1918, under its new leader Éamon de Valera, Sinn Féin had come to favour achieving separation from Britain by means of an armed uprising if necessary and the establishment of an independent republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the 1916 Easter Rising the party's ranks were swelled by participants and supporters of the rebellion as they were freed from British prisons and internment camps, and at its 1917 Ard Fheis (annual conference) de Valera was elected leader and the new, more radical policy adopted.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Prior to 1916, Sinn Féin had been a fringe movement having a limited cooperative alliance with William O'Brien's All-for-Ireland League and enjoyed little electoral success.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, between the Easter Rising of that year and the 1918 general election, the party's popularity increased dramatically.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin demonstrated its new electoral capability in four by-election successes in 1917 in which Count Plunkett, Joseph McGuinness, de Valera and W.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave were each elected, although it lost three by-elections in early 1918 before winning two more with Patrick McCartan and Arthur Griffith.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In one case there were unproven allegations of electoral fraud.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had benefitted from a number of factors in the 1918 elections, including demographic changes and political factors.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate in 1918, as with the entire electorate throughout the United Kingdom, had changed in two major ways since the preceding general election.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Firstly, there was a "generational" change because of the First World War, which meant that the British general election due in 1915 had not taken place.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As a result, no election took place between 1910 and 1918, the longest gap in modern British and Irish constitutional history until then (it was superseded in Britain in 1935–45).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Secondly, the franchise had been greatly extended by the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This granted voting rights to women (albeit only those over 30) for the first time, and gave all men over 21 and military servicemen over 19 a vote in parliamentary elections without property qualifications.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate increased from around 700,000 to about two million.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Overall, a new generation of young voters, and the sudden influx of women over thirty, meant that vast numbers of new voters of unknown voter affiliation existed, changing dramatically the composition of the Irish electorate.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Six MPs stood under a different political affiliation from the December 1910 general election.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] One MP stood under a different political affiliation from their by-election victory.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Voting in most Irish constituencies occurred on Saturday, 14 December 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] While the rest of the United Kingdom fought the 'Khaki election' on other issues involving the British parties, in Ireland four major political parties had national appeal.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] These were the IPP, Sinn Féin, the Irish Unionist Party and the Irish Labour Party.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionist Party favoured continuance of the union with Britain (along with its subordinate, the Ulster Unionist Labour Association, who fought as Labour Unionists).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] A number of other small nationalist parties also took part.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ireland had 105 seats elected from 103 constituencies.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ninety-nine seats were elected from single-seat geographical constituencies under the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There were two two-seat constituencies: Dublin University (Trinity College) elected two MPs under the single transferable vote and Cork City elected two MPs under the bloc voting system.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In addition to ordinary geographical constituencies there were three university constituencies: the Queen's University of Belfast (which returned a Unionist), Dublin University (which returned two Unionists) and the National University (which returned a member of Sinn Féin).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 105 seats, 25 were uncontested, with a Sinn Féin candidate winning unopposed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Seventeen of these seats were in Munster.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In some cases it was because there was a certain winner in Sinn Féin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dillon was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1880.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He resigned in 1883 but was re-elected in 1885.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Donovan contested the Donegal South constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Esmonde was first elected to the Dublin South constituency in 1885.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell contested the Longford constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell was first elected to the Cavan West constituency in 1895.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Hazleton contested the Louth constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Kilbride was first elected to the Kerry South constituency in 1887.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He retired in 1900 but was re-elected in 1903.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Meehan contested the Queen's County constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Nugent contested the Dublin St Michan's constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1885.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1892 but regained it in 1905.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Dowd was first elected to the Sligo North constituency in 1900.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Shee contested the Waterford County constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch contested the Battersea South constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch was first elected to the Galway Borough constituency in 1901.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1903 following his conviction but was re-elected in 1909.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Stepney Limehouse constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Gwynn contested the Dublin University constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Westmeath constituency in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In this election, 75 candidates who had never previously been elected to Parliament were elected.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin candidates won 73 seats out of 105, but four party candidates (Arthur Griffith, Éamon de Valera, Eoin MacNeill and Liam Mellows) were elected for two constituencies and so the total number of individual Sinn Féin MPs elected was 69.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Despite the isolated allegations of intimidation and electoral fraud on the part of both republicans and unionists, the election was seen as a landslide victory for Sinn Féin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin received 46.9% of votes island-wide, and 65% of votes in the area that became the Irish Free State.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the 46.9% is not the total result of the overall success of Sinn Féin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That figure only accounts for 48 seats that they won because in 25 of the other constituencies the other parties did not contest them, and Sinn Féin won them unopposed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Most of these constituencies were Sinn Féin strongholds.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It has been estimated that, had the 25 seats been contested, Sinn Féin would have received at least 53% of the vote island-wide.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, this is a conservative estimate and the percentage would likely have been higher.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin also did not contest four seats due to a deal with the IPP (see below).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Labour, who had pulled out in the south under instructions to 'wait', polled better in Belfast than Sinn Féin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Within the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, Sinn Féin achieved 400,269 votes in the contested seats out of 606,117 total votes cast which amounted to a huge landslide of 66.0% in the vote and winning 70 out of the 75 constituencies.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Unionist Party won 22 seats and 25.3% of the vote island-wide (29.2% when Labour Unionist candidates are included), becoming the second-largest party in terms of MPs.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The success of the unionists, who won 26 seats overall, was largely limited to Ulster.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Otherwise, southern unionists were elected only in the constituencies of Rathmines and Dublin University which returned two.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that later became the Irish Free State and then the Republic of Ireland, the Irish Unionist Alliance polled 37,218 votes from 101,839 total votes cast for other parties in the constituencies that they stood a candidate.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, if all of the total votes in the contested seats where the Irish Unionist Alliance did not stand are included there was a total of 606,117 votes cast, which converts the Irish Unionist Alliance share of the vote in the 26 counties to just 6.1%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] With the one Independent Unionist being elected for Dublin University adding 0.1% in total with 793 votes to give 6.2% across the 26 counties and only 3 seats won by the Unionists.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP suffered a catastrophic defeat including the loss of its leader, John Dillon.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It won only six seats in Ireland, its losses exaggerated by the "first-past-the-post" system which gave it a share of seats far short of its much larger share of the vote (21.7%) and the number of seats it would have won under a "proportional representation" ballot system.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] All but one of its seats were in Ulster.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The exception was Waterford City, the seat previously held by John Redmond, who had died earlier in the year, and retained by his son Captain William Redmond.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Four of their Ulster seats were part of the deal to avoid unionist victories which saved some for the party but may have cost it the support of Protestant voters elsewhere.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP came close to winning other seats in County Louth and Wexford South, and in general their support held up better in the north and east of the island.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party was represented in Westminster by seven MPs because T.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor won the Liverpool Scotland seat he had held since the 1885 election due to Irish emigrant votes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The remnants of the IPP in time became the Nationalist Party of Northern Ireland under the leadership of Joseph Devlin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, the Irish Parliamentary Party won 181,320 votes out of 606,117 total votes cast in the contested seats, amounting to a 26.0% vote share.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] If the Independent Home Rule Nationalists are included there were 11,162 votes which comes to 1.8% and a vote share of 27.8% for the Nationalists.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Parliamentary Party held on to just 2 seats in the 26 counties that became Southern Ireland and then the Irish Free State.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster (nine counties), Unionists won 23 out of the 38 seats with Sinn Féin gaining ten and the Irish Parliamentary Party five.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was a limited electoral pact brokered by Roman Catholic Cardinal Michael Logue in December between Sinn Féin and the Nationalist IPP in eight seats.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, it only concluded after nominations closed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin instructed its supporters to vote IPP in Armagh South, despite no Unionist candidate (79 SF votes), Down South (33 SF votes for Éamon de Valera), Tyrone North-East (56 SF votes) and Donegal East (46 SF votes).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP instructed its supporters to vote Sinn Féin in Fermanagh South (132 IPP votes) which had no Unionist candidate, Londonderry City (120 IPP votes) where Eoin MacNeill narrowly beat the Unionist, and Tyrone North-West also against a Unionist but where no IPP candidate was nominated.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The discipline of voters, when faced with two rival nationalist candidates and with only a post-nomination pact, was impressive.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The pact only broke down in Down East where a Unionist won as the IPP candidate refused to participate, thus splitting the Catholic nationalist vote.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was no pact in Belfast Falls which Joe Devlin (IPP) won with 8,488 votes against 3,245 for Éamon de Valera (SF) although no Unionist stood.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The only other Belfast seat contested by both nationalist parties was Duncairn against Edward Carson; otherwise, Sinn Féin stood alone in seven seats reaching double figures in two.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Monaghan North was won by Sinn Féin's Ernest Blythe in a three-cornered fight against both IPP and Unionist candidates.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the Monaghan South, and Donegal North, South and West seats, despite no Unionist standing, Sinn Féin won all four against IPP candidates.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin took the two (uncontested) Cavan seats with Arthur Griffith taking his second in Cavan East as well as that of Tyrone North West.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In six contested seats no Unionist stood.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists won a clear majority of the 38 Ulster seats including eight of the nine in Belfast.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the six Ulster counties which formed the future Northern Ireland, Unionists won 23 of the 30 seats.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On 21 January 1919, 27 (out of 101 elected) members representing thirty constituencies answered the roll of Dáil Éireann—the Irish for "Assembly of Ireland".
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Invitations to attend the Dáil had been sent to all 100 men and one woman who had been elected on 14 December 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Eoin MacNeill had been elected for both Londonderry City and the National University of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Thirty-three republicans were unable to attend as they were in prison, most of them without trial since 17 May 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Pierce McCan (of Tipperary East), who died in prison, would have brought the total to thirty-four.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 69 republicans elected, most had fought in the Easter Rising.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In accordance with the Sinn Féin manifesto, their elected members refused to attend Westminster, having instead formed their own parliament.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dáil Éireann was, according to John Patrick McCarthy, the revolutionary government under which the Irish War of Independence was fought and which sought international recognition.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Maryann Gialanella Valiulis says that having justified its existence, the Dáil provided itself with a theoretical framework and set about the process of state-building.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] After having dominated Irish politics for four decades, the IPP was so decimated by its massive defeat that it dissolved soon after the election.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As mentioned above, its remains became the Northern Ireland-based Nationalist Party, which survived in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The British administration and unionists refused to recognise the Dáil.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] At its first meeting attended by 27 deputies (others were still imprisoned or impaired) on 21 January 1919 the Dáil issued a Declaration of Independence and proclaimed itself the parliament of a new state, the Irish Republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On the same day, in unconnected circumstances, two members of the Royal Irish Constabulary guarding gelignite were killed in the Soloheadbeg Ambush by members of the Irish Volunteers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Although it had not ordered this incident, the course of events soon drove the Dáil to recognise the Volunteers as the army of the Irish Republic and the ambush as an act of war against Great Britain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Volunteers therefore changed their name, in August, to the Irish Republican Army.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The train of events set in motion by the elections would eventually bring about the creation of the Irish Free State as a British dominion in 1922.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That state became the first internationally recognised independent Irish state in 1931, when the Statute of Westminster removed virtually all of the UK Parliament's remaining authority over the Free State and the other dominions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Free State eventually evolved into the modern Republic of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The leaders of the Sinn Féin candidates elected in 1918, such as de Valera, Michael Collins and W.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave, came to dominate Irish politics.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] De Valera, for example, would hold some form of elected office from his first election as an MP in a by-election in 1917 until 1973.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The two major parties in the Republic of Ireland today, Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael, are both descendants of Sinn Féin, which first enjoyed substantial electoral success in 1918.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The **1979 oil crisis**, sometimes referred to as the **second oil crisis** (in reference to the 1973 oil crisis), refers to the drop in oil production in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution that led to an energy crisis in 1979.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Although the global oil supply only decreased by approximately four percent, the oil markets' reaction raised the price of crude oil drastically over the next 12 months, more than doubling it to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3), equivalent to $175 per barrel ($1,101/m3) in 2025.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The sudden increase in price was connected with fuel shortages similar to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, following the onset of the Iran–Iraq War, oil production in Iran fell drastically.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Iraq's oil production also dropped significantly, triggering economic recessions worldwide.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices did not return to pre-crisis levels until the mid-1980s.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices after 1980 began a steady decline over the next 20 years, except for a brief uptick during the Gulf War, which then reached a 60% fall-off in the 1990s.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Mexico, Nigeria, and Venezuela's major oil exporters expanded their production during this time.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The Soviet Union became the largest oil producer in the world, and oil from the North Sea and Alaska flooded the market.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1978, a strike by 37,000 workers at Iran's nationalized oil refineries reduced production from 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) per day to about 1.5 million barrels (240,000 m3).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] By bringing navy personnel into crude oil production operations, the government fixed short-term disruptions and by end of November the output came back to almost normal level.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] On January 16, 1979, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and his wife, Farah Pahlavi, left Iran at the behest of Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar, who sought to calm the situation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] After the departure of the Shah, Ayatollah Khomeini became the new leader of Iran.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The rise in oil prices benefited a few members of the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC), which made record profits.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Under the new Iranian government, oil exports later resumed but production was inconsistent and at a lower volume, further raising prices.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Mana Al Otaiba, increased production to offset most of the decline, and by early 1979 the overall loss in worldwide production was roughly four percent.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The war between Iran and Iraq in 1980 caused a further 7 percent drop in worldwide production.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] OPEC production was surpassed by other exporters such as the United States, as OPEC member nations were divided amongst themselves.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia, a "swing producer", tried to gain back the market share after 1985, increasing production and causing downward pressure on prices, making high-cost oil production facilities less profitable.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The oil crisis had a mixed impact on the United States.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Richard Nixon had imposed price controls on domestic oil as a result of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Since then, gasoline price controls had been repealed, but those on domestic oil remained.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The Jimmy Carter administration began a phased deregulation of oil prices on April 5, 1979, when the average price of crude oil was US$15.85 per barrel ($100/m3).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Starting with the Iranian revolution, the price of crude oil rose to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3) over the next 12 months (its all-time highest real price until March 3, 2008).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Deregulating domestic oil price controls allowed U.S. oil output to rise sharply from the large Prudhoe Bay fields, while oil imports fell sharply.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Although not directly related, the near-disaster at Three Mile Island on March 28, 1979, also increased anxiety about energy policy and availability.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Due to memories of the oil shortage in 1973, motorists soon began panic buying, and long lines appeared at gas stations, as they had six years earlier.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The average vehicle of the time consumed between two and three liters (about 0.5–0.8 gallons) of gasoline an hour while idling, and it was estimated that Americans wasted up to 150,000 barrels (24,000 m3) of oil per day idling their engines in the lines at gas stations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In 1979, the amount of oil sold in the United States was only 3.5 percent less than the record set for oil sold in 1978.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] A telephone poll of 1,600 American adults conducted by the Associated Press and NBC News and released in early May 1979 found that only 37 percent of Americans thought the energy shortages were real, nine percent were not sure, and 54 percent thought the energy shortages were a hoax.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Many politicians proposed gas rationing.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] One such proponent was Harry Hughes, Governor of Maryland, who proposed odd-even rationing (only people with an odd-numbered license plate could purchase gas on an odd-numbered day), as was used during the 1973 Oil Crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Several states implemented odd-even gas rationing, including California, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Texas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Coupons for gasoline rationing were printed but were never actually used during the 1979 crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] On July 15, 1979, President Carter outlined his plans to reduce oil imports and improve energy efficiency in his "Crisis of Confidence" speech, sometimes known as the "malaise" speech.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In the speech, Carter encouraged citizens to do what they could to reduce their use of energy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] He had already installed water tank heating solar panels on the roof of the White House and a wood-burning stove in the living quarters.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The panels were removed in 1986, reportedly for roof maintenance, during the administration of his successor, Ronald Reagan.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] A speech Carter gave in April 1977 argued that the oil crisis was "the moral equivalent of war".
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1979, Iranian revolutionaries seized the American Embassy, and Carter imposed an embargo on Iranian oil.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In January 1980, he issued the Carter Doctrine, declaring: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States".
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Additionally, as part of his administration's efforts at deregulation, Carter proposed removing price controls that had been imposed by the Richard Nixon administration before the 1973 crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Carter agreed to remove price controls in phases.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] They were fully dismantled in 1981 under Reagan.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Carter also said he would impose a windfall profit tax on oil companies.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] While the regulated price of domestic oil was kept to $6 a barrel, the world market price was $30.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, the U.S. government established the Synthetic Fuels Corporation to produce an alternative to imported fossil fuels.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] When the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent between 1978 and 1980, the oil-producing areas of Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska began experiencing an economic boom and population inflows.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] According to a 2019 study, individuals who were between the ages of 15 and 18 during the 1979 oil crisis were substantially less likely to use cars once they were in their mid-30s.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] In response to the high oil prices of the 1970s, industrial nations took steps to reduce their dependence on the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC) oil.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Electric utilities worldwide switched from oil to coal, natural gas, or nuclear power.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] National governments initiated multibillion-dollar research programs to develop alternatives to oil and commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] By 1986, daily worldwide demand for oil dropped by 5 million barrels but, non-OPEC production rose by an even-larger amount.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Consequently, OPEC's market share reduced from 50 percent in 1979 to 29 percent in 1985.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] At the time, Detroit's "Big Three" automakers (Ford, Chrysler, GM) were marketing downsized full-sized automobiles like the Chevrolet Caprice, the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and the Dodge St.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Regis which met the CAFE fuel economy mandates passed in 1978.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit's response to the growing popularity of imported compacts like the Toyota Corolla and the Volkswagen Rabbit was the Chevrolet Citation and the Ford Fairmont.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Ford replaced the Ford Pinto with the Ford Escort and Chrysler, on the verge of bankruptcy, introduced the Dodge Aries K.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] GM was having unfavorable market reactions to the Citation and introduced the Chevrolet Corsica and Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 which sold better.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] GM also replaced the Chevrolet Monza, introducing the 1982 Chevrolet Cavalier which was better received.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Ford experienced a similar market rejection of the Fairmont and introduced the front-wheel-drive Ford Tempo in 1984.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit was not well prepared for the sudden rise in fuel prices, and imported brands, primarily the Asian models, which were mass-marketed and had a lower manufacturing cost as opposed to British and West German brands.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] A year after the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Japanese exports later displaced the automotive market once dominated by lower-tier European manufacturers (Renault, Fiat, Opel, Peugeot, MG, Triumph, Citroen).
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Triumph, Simca) or withdraw from the U.S. market, especially in the wake of grey market automobiles or the inability of the vehicle to meet DOT requirements, from emission requirements to automotive lighting.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] Many imported brands utilized fuel-saving technologies such as fuel injection and multi-valve engines over the common use of carburetors.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] The overall fuel economy of cars in the United States increased from about 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) in 1979 to 18 mpg‑US (13 L/100 km; 22 mpg‑imp) by 1985 and 20 mpg‑US (12 L/100 km; 24 mpg‑imp) by 1990.
[src:republic-of-ireland/1979-oil-crisis] This was one factor leading to the subsequent 1980s oil glut.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:republic-of-ireland/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] .ie was registered on 27 January 1988 and a year later the registration of .ie domain names was delegated by Jon Postel to the Computing Services Computer Centre of University College Dublin, then headed by Dennis Jennings.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In 2000, the administration of the .ie domain was sub-delegated by UCD to a new company, IE Domain Registry Limited.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The Computing Services Computer Centre of University College Dublin remains the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority's sponsoring organisation for the .ie domain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In 2000, the Oireachtas (bicameral parliament of Ireland) enacted a law giving the Minister for Public Enterprise the power to make regulations regarding the registration of .ie domain names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In 2007 this power was transferred to the Commission for Communications Regulation (ComReg).
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The IEDR is considered more conservative than other similar authorities and places certain restrictions on registration.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The .ie ccTLD is primarily a business orientated ccTLD for Irish businesses and businesses doing business in or with Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] It has allowed personal domain name (PDN) registrations, though these would only account for approximately 1% of the number of .ie domain registrations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] An individual is allowed to register their own name or a variant of it with a utilities bill or passport as proof of entitlement.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Registration policies have been liberalised somewhat in recent years and rules such as the one against registering generic domain names have been dropped.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The .ie ccTLD is a managed ccTLD where applicants for .ie domain names have to provide proof of entitlement to the domain that they want to register.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In August 2017 IEDR began a consultation on removing this restriction and allowing first-come first-served registration; the requirement of a connection to Ireland will remain.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Registration is restricted to entities with a connection to Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Thus, American singer Melanie was not allowed to register `Melan.ie`; whereas Microsoft, which has a corporate presence in Ireland, was allowed to register `Modern.IE`, a domain hack whose full name reflects its purpose as support for IE (Internet Explorer).
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In February 2016 IEDR began a consultation on the introduction of internationalized domain names, in particular the vowel + "fada" characters (á é í ó ú) used in Irish orthography.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] IDN domains were launched on a phased basis starting with existing domain holders on 23 October 2016, with general availability starting on 17 November 2016.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The typical registration fee via accredited .ie registrars is approximately €25 (plus VAT of €5.75).
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Registration is free for charities registered with the Revenue Commissioners.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Evidence of entitlement to the domain name (such as evidence of entitlement to use a particular business name via a Registered Business Name certificate or registered company name) and a connection with the island of Ireland are required for registration.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The requirement to provide a 'claim to the name' was removed in March 2018, following public consultation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] There is no official second-level domain policy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] A number of domain names, typically those of other TLDs, two letter domains and potentially offensive domains are forbidden from being registered.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Nevertheless, the Government of Ireland began using the `.gov.ie` domain where once it used `irlgov.ie`.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Some government departments continue to use their own non `gov.ie` domains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Prior to 16 December 2015, two character domains consisting of one letter and one number were permitted, but two-letter domain registrations were not permitted.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The only exceptions to the old two letter rule were `ul.ie`, which was registered by the University of Limerick before the rule came into effect, and `ns.ie`, which is used for the .ie name servers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] The domains in the *forbidden* category will return a record for a WHOIS query but they are not in the .ie zone.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] In June 2015, the IEDR announced that two-letter names would soon be available; a 30-day registration began in November for a go-live date of 16 December 2015.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Where there were multiple applicants for a given combination, an auction was held in early 2016.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] As of October 2025, there were 332,297 registered .ie domain names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] This has surpassed the number of Irish-owned and or hosted .com domain names.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] It is the preferred extension for new Irish businesses.
[src:republic-of-ireland/ie] Approximately 140 new .ie domains are registered each working day.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Free State was created with Dominion status in 1922, following the Anglo-Irish Treaty.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 1937, a new constitution was adopted, in which the state was named "Ireland" and effectively became a republic, with an elected non-executive president.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It was officially declared a republic in 1949, following The Republic of Ireland Act 1948.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland became a member of the United Nations in 1955.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It joined the European Communities (EC), the predecessor of the European Union (EU), in 1973.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The state had no formal relations with Northern Ireland for most of the 20th century, but the 1980s and 1990s saw the British and Irish governments working with Northern Irish parties to resolve the conflict that had become known as the Troubles.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Since the signing of the Good Friday Agreement in 1998, the Irish government and Northern Irish government have co-operated on a number of policy areas under the North/South Ministerial Council created by the Agreement.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland is a developed country with a quality of life ranked sixth in the world by the 2024 Human Development Index Report adjusted for inequality.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It also ranks highly in healthcare, economic freedom and freedom of the press.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] According to the Global Peace Index, Ireland was the second most peaceful country worldwide in 2024.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It is a member of the EU and a founding member of the Council of Europe and the OECD.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish government has followed a policy of military neutrality through non-alignment since before World War II, and the country is consequently not a member of NATO, although it is a member of the Partnership for Peace and certain aspects of PESCO.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's economy is advanced, with one of Europe's major financial hubs being centred on Dublin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It ranks among the top five wealthiest countries in the world in terms of both GDP and GNI per capita.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] After joining the EC, the country's government enacted a series of liberal economic policies that helped to boost economic growth between 1995 and 2007, a time now often referred to as the Celtic Tiger period.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] A recession and reversal in growth then followed during the Great Recession, which was exacerbated by the bursting of the Irish property bubble.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Great Recession lasted until 2014, and was followed by a new period of strong economic growth.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The names *Ireland* and *Éire* both derive from Old Irish *Ériu*, which in turn comes from Proto-Celtic *ɸīweriyū* meaning "fertile soil".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Classical Latin name for the island of Ireland, *Ivernia*, also comes from this same root, and it remains a popular, poetic synonym for Ireland to this day (usually respelled "*Hibernia*", under the influence of *hibernum*, the Latin word for "winter").
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The state created in 1922, comprising 26 of the 32 counties of Ireland, was "styled and known as the Irish Free State" (*Saorstát Éireann*).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Constitution of Ireland, adopted in 1937, says that "the name of the State is *Éire*, or, in the English language, Ireland".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Section 2 of the Republic of Ireland Act 1948 states, "It is hereby declared that the description of the State shall be the Republic of Ireland." The 1948 Act does not *name* the state "Republic of Ireland", because to have done so would have put it in conflict with the Constitution.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The government of the United Kingdom used the name "Eire" (without the diacritic) and, from 1949, "Republic of Ireland", for the state.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It was not until the 1998 Good Friday Agreement, when the state dropped its claim to Northern Ireland, that it began calling the state "Ireland".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The state is also informally called "the Republic", "Southern Ireland" or "the South"; especially when distinguishing the state from the island or when discussing Northern Ireland ("the North").
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Irish republicans reserve the name "Ireland" for the whole island and often refer to the state as "the Free State", "the 26 Counties", or "the South of Ireland".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This is a "response to the partitionist view [...] that Ireland stops at the border".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] From the Act of Union on 1 January 1801, until 6 December 1922, the island of Ireland was part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] During the Great Famine, from 1845 to 1849, the island's population of over 8 million fell by 30%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] One million Irish died of starvation and disease and another 1.5 million emigrated, mostly to the United States.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This set the pattern of emigration for the century to come, resulting in constant population decline up to the 1960s.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] From 1874, and particularly under Charles Stewart Parnell from 1880, the Irish Parliamentary Party gained prominence.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This was firstly through widespread agrarian agitation via the Irish Land League, which won land reforms for tenants in the form of the Irish Land Acts, and secondly through its attempts to achieve Home Rule, via two unsuccessful bills which would have granted Ireland limited national autonomy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] These led to "grass-roots" control of national affairs, under the Local Government Act 1898, that had been in the hands of landlord-dominated grand juries of the Protestant Ascendancy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Home Rule seemed certain when the Parliament Act 1911 abolished the veto of the House of Lords, and John Redmond secured the Third Home Rule Act in 1914.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] However, the Unionist movement had been growing since 1886 among Irish Protestants after the introduction of the first home rule bill, fearing discrimination and loss of economic and social privileges if Irish Catholics achieved real political power.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In the late 19th and early 20th-century unionism was particularly strong in parts of Ulster, where industrialisation was more common in contrast to the more agrarian rest of the island, and where the Protestant population was more prominent, with a majority in four counties.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Under the leadership of the Dublin-born Sir Edward Carson of the Irish Unionist Party and the Ulsterman Sir James Craig of the Ulster Unionist Party, unionists became strongly militant, forming Ulster Volunteers in order to oppose "the Coercion of Ulster".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] After the Home Rule Bill passed parliament in May 1914, to avoid rebellion with Ulster, the British Prime Minister H.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Asquith introduced an Amending Bill reluctantly conceded to by the Irish Party leadership.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This provided for the temporary exclusion of Ulster from the workings of the bill for a trial period of six years, with an as yet undecided new set of measures to be introduced for the area to be temporarily excluded.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Though it received the Royal Assent and was placed on the statute books in 1914, the implementation of the Third Home Rule Act was suspended until after the First World War which defused the threat of civil war in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] With the hope of ensuring the implementation of the Act at the end of the war through Ireland's engagement in the war, Redmond and the Irish National Volunteers supported the UK and its Allies.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] 175,000 men joined Irish regiments of the 10th (Irish) and 16th (Irish) divisions of the New British Army, while Unionists joined the 36th (Ulster) divisions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The remainder of the Irish Volunteers, who refused Redmond and opposed any support of the UK, launched an armed insurrection against British rule in the 1916 Easter Rising, together with the Irish Citizen Army and other militant Irish nationalist groups.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This commenced on 24 April 1916 with the Proclamation of the Republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] After a week of heavy fighting, primarily in Dublin, the surviving rebels were forced to surrender their positions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The majority were imprisoned, with fifteen of the prisoners (including most of the leaders and all of the Proclamation signatories) executed for taking part in armed rebellion and waging war against the British Crown, court-martialed under the Defence of the Realm Act.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This included Patrick Pearse, the Commander-in-Chief of the Irish rebel forces, and James Connolly, socialist and founder of the Industrial Workers of the World union and both the Irish and Scottish Labour movements.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Rising, and the executions and arrests, together with the Conscription Crisis of 1918, had the effect of changing public opinion in Ireland against the British Government.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In January 1919, after the December 1918 general election, 73 of Ireland's 105 Members of Parliament (MPs) elected were Sinn Féin members who were elected on a platform of abstentionism from the British House of Commons.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In January 1919, they set up an Irish parliament called Dáil Éireann.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This first Dáil issued a declaration of independence and proclaimed an Irish Republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The declaration was mainly a restatement of the 1916 Proclamation with the additional provision that Ireland was no longer a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Republic's Ministry of Dáil Éireann sent a delegation under Ceann Comhairle (Head of Council, or Speaker, of the Dáil) Seán T.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] O'Kelly to the Paris Peace Conference of 1919, but it was not admitted.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] After the War of Independence and truce called in July 1921, representatives of the British government and the five Irish treaty delegates, led by Arthur Griffith, Robert Barton and Michael Collins, negotiated the Anglo-Irish Treaty in London from 11 October to 6 December 1921.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish delegates set up headquarters at Hans Place in Knightsbridge, and it was here in private discussions that the decision was taken on 5 December to recommend the treaty to Dáil Éireann.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] On 7 January 1922, the Second Dáil ratified the Treaty by 64 votes to 57.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In accordance with the treaty, on 6 December 1922 the entire island of Ireland became a self-governing Dominion called the Irish Free State (*Saorstát Éireann*).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Under the Constitution of the Irish Free State, the Parliament of Northern Ireland had the option to leave the Irish Free State one month later and return to the United Kingdom.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] During the intervening period, the powers of the Parliament of the Irish Free State and Executive Council of the Irish Free State did not extend to Northern Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Northern Ireland exercised its right under the treaty to leave the new Dominion and rejoined the United Kingdom on 8 December 1922.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The country had a governor-general (representing the monarch), a bicameral parliament, a cabinet called the "Executive Council", and a prime minister called the President of the Executive Council.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Civil War (June 1922 – May 1923) was the consequence of the ratification of the Anglo-Irish Treaty and the creation of the Irish Free State.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Anti-treaty forces, led by Éamon de Valera, objected to the fact that acceptance of the treaty abolished the Irish Republic of 1919 to which they had sworn loyalty, arguing in the face of public support for the settlement that the "people have no right to do wrong".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] They objected most to the fact that the state would remain part of the British Empire and that members of the Free State Parliament would have to swear what the anti-treaty side saw as an oath of fidelity to the British king.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Pro-treaty forces, led by Michael Collins, argued that the treaty gave "not the ultimate freedom that all nations aspire to and develop, but the freedom to achieve it".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] At the start of the war, the Irish Republican Army (IRA) split into two opposing camps: a pro-treaty IRA and an anti-treaty IRA.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The pro-treaty IRA disbanded and joined the new National Army.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] British supplies of artillery, aircraft, machine-guns and ammunition boosted pro-treaty forces, and the threat of a return of Crown forces to the Free State removed any doubts about the necessity of enforcing the treaty.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Lack of public support for the anti-treaty forces (often called the Irregulars) and the determination of the government to overcome the Irregulars contributed significantly to their defeat.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Following a national plebiscite in July 1937, the new Constitution of Ireland (*Bunreacht na hÉireann*) came into force on 29 December 1937.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This replaced the Constitution of the Irish Free State and declared that the name of the state is *Éire*, or "Ireland" in the English language.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] While Articles 2 and 3 of the Constitution defined the national territory to be the whole island, they also confined the state's jurisdiction to the area that had been the Irish Free State.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The former Irish Free State government had abolished the Office of Governor-General in December 1936.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Although the constitution established the office of President of Ireland, the question over whether Ireland was a republic remained open.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Diplomats were accredited to the king, but the president exercised all internal functions of a head of state.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] For instance, the President gave assent to new laws with his own authority, without reference to King George VI who was only an "organ", that was provided for by statute law.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland remained neutral during World War II, a period it described as The Emergency.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's Dominion status was terminated with the passage of The Republic of Ireland Act 1948, which came into force on 18 April 1949 and declared that the state was a republic.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] At the time, a declaration of a republic terminated Commonwealth membership.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This rule was changed 10 days after Ireland declared itself a republic, with the London Declaration of 28 April 1949.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland did not reapply when the rules were altered to permit republics to join.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Later, the Crown of Ireland Act 1542 was repealed in Ireland by the Statute Law Revision (Pre-Union Irish Statutes) Act 1962.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland became a member of the United Nations in December 1955, after having been denied membership because of its neutral stance during the Second World War and not supporting the Allied cause.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] At the time, joining the UN involved a commitment to using force to deter aggression by one state against another if the UN thought it was necessary.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Interest towards membership of the European Communities (EC) developed in Ireland during the 1950s, with consideration also given to membership of the European Free Trade Area.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] As the United Kingdom intended on EC membership, Ireland applied for membership in July 1961 due to the substantial economic linkages with the United Kingdom.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The founding EC members remained sceptical regarding Ireland's economic capacity, neutrality, and unattractive protectionist policy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Many Irish economists and politicians realised that economic policy reform was necessary.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The prospect of EC membership became doubtful in 1963 when French President General Charles de Gaulle stated that France opposed Britain's accession, which ceased negotiations with all other candidate countries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 1969 his successor, Georges Pompidou, was not opposed to British and Irish membership.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Negotiations began and in 1972 the Treaty of Accession was signed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] A referendum was held later that year which confirmed Ireland's entry into the bloc, and it finally joined the EC as a member state on 1 January 1973.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The economic crisis of the late 1970s was fuelled by the Fianna Fáil government's budget, the abolition of the car tax, excessive borrowing, and global economic instability including the 1979 oil crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] There were significant policy changes from 1989 onwards, with economic reform, tax cuts, welfare reform, an increase in competition, and a ban on borrowing to fund current spending.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This policy began in 1989–1992 by the Fianna Fáil/Progressive Democrats government, and continued by the subsequent Fianna Fáil/Labour government and Fine Gael/Labour/Democratic Left government.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland became one of the world's fastest growing economies by the late 1990s in what was known as the Celtic Tiger period, which lasted until the Great Recession.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Since 2014, Ireland has experienced increased economic activity.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In the Northern Ireland question, the British and Irish governments started to seek a peaceful resolution to the violent conflict involving many paramilitaries and the British Army in Northern Ireland known as "The Troubles".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] A peace settlement for Northern Ireland, known as the Good Friday Agreement, was approved in 1998 in referendums north and south of the border.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] As part of the peace settlement, the territorial claim to Northern Ireland in Articles 2 and 3 of the Constitution of Ireland was removed by referendum.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In its white paper on Brexit the United Kingdom government reiterated its commitment to the Good Friday Agreement.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] With regard to Northern Ireland's status, it said that the UK Government's "clearly-stated preference is to retain Northern Ireland's current constitutional position: as part of the UK, but with strong links to Ireland".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The state extends over an area of about five-sixths (70,273 km2 or 27,133 sq mi) of the island of Ireland (84,421 km2 or 32,595 sq mi), with Northern Ireland constituting the remainder.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The island is bounded to the north and west by the Atlantic Ocean and to the northeast by the North Channel.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] To the east, the Irish Sea connects to the Atlantic Ocean via St George's Channel and the Celtic Sea to the southwest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The western landscape mostly consists of rugged cliffs, hills and mountains.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The central lowlands are extensively covered with glacial deposits of clay and sand, as well as significant areas of bogland and several lakes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The highest point is Carrauntoohil (1,038.6 m or 3,407 ft), located in the MacGillycuddy's Reeks mountain range in the southwest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] River Shannon, which traverses the central lowlands, is the longest river in Ireland at 386 kilometres or 240 miles in length.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The west coast is more rugged than the east, with numerous islands, peninsulas, headlands and bays.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland is one of the least forested countries in Europe.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Until the end of the Middle Ages, the land was heavily forested.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Native species include deciduous trees such as oak, ash, hazel, birch, alder, willow, aspen, elm, rowan and hawthorn, as well as evergreen trees such Scots pine, yew, holly and strawberry trees.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The growth of blanket bog and the extensive clearing of woodland for farming are believed to be the main causes of deforestation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Today, only about 10% of Ireland is woodland, most of which is non-native conifer plantations, and only 2% of which is native woodland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The average woodland cover in European countries is over 33%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] According to *Coillte*, a state-owned forestry business, the country's climate gives Ireland one of the fastest growth rates for forests in Europe.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Hedgerows, which are traditionally used to define land boundaries, are an important substitute for woodland habitat, providing refuge for native wild flora and a wide range of insect, bird and mammal species.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It is home to two terrestrial ecoregions: Celtic broadleaf forests and North Atlantic moist mixed forests.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Agriculture accounts for about 64% of the total land area.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This has resulted in limited land to preserve natural habitats, in particular for larger wild mammals with greater territorial requirements.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The long history of agricultural production coupled with modern agricultural methods, such as pesticide and fertiliser use, has placed pressure on biodiversity.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Atlantic Ocean and the warming influence of the Gulf Stream affect weather patterns in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Temperatures differ regionally, with central and eastern areas tending to be more extreme.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] However, due to a temperate oceanic climate, temperatures are seldom lower than −5 °C (23 °F) in winter or higher than 26 °C (79 °F) in summer.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The highest temperature recorded in Ireland was 33.3 °C (91.9 °F) on 26 June 1887 at Kilkenny Castle in Kilkenny, while the lowest temperature recorded was −19.1 °C (−2.4 °F) at Markree Castle in Sligo.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Rainfall is more prevalent during winter months and less so during the early months of summer.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Southwestern areas experience the most rainfall as a result of south westerly winds, while Dublin receives the least.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Sunshine duration is highest in the southeast of the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The far north and west are two of the windiest regions in Europe, with great potential for wind energy generation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland normally gets between 1100 and 1600 hours of sunshine each year, most areas averaging between 3.25 and 3.75 hours a day.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The sunniest months are May and June, which average between 5 and 6.5 hours per day over most of the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The extreme southeast gets most sunshine, averaging over 7 hours a day in early summer.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] December is the dullest month, with an average daily sunshine ranging from about 1 hour in the north to almost 2 hours in the extreme southeast.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The sunniest summer in the 100 years from 1881 to 1980 was 1887, according to measurements made at the Phoenix Park in Dublin; 1980 was the dullest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland is a constitutional republic with a parliamentary system of government.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The President serves as head of state, is elected for a seven-year term, and may be re-elected once.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Restrictive nomination rules for presidential candidates resulted in 12.9% spoilt votes during the 2025 Irish presidential election.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The President is primarily a figurehead, but is entrusted with certain constitutional powers with the advice of the Council of State.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The office has absolute discretion in some areas, such as referring a bill to the Supreme Court for a judgment on its constitutionality.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Catherine Connolly became the tenth President of Ireland on 11 November 2025.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Taoiseach (Prime Minister) serves as the head of government and is appointed by the President upon the nomination of the Dáil.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Most Taoisigh have served as the leader of the political party that gains the most seats in national elections.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It has become customary for coalitions to form a government, as there has not been a single-party government since 1989.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Dáil has 174 members (Teachtaí Dála) elected to represent multi-seat constituencies under the system of proportional representation by means of the single transferable vote.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Seanad is composed of sixty members, with eleven nominated by the Taoiseach, six elected by two university constituencies, and 43 elected by public representatives from panels of candidates established on a vocational basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The government is constitutionally limited to fifteen members.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] No more than two members can be selected from the Seanad, and the Taoiseach, Tánaiste (deputy prime minister) and Minister for Finance must be members of the Dáil.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Dáil must be dissolved within five years of its first meeting following the previous election, and a general election for members of the Dáil must take place no later than thirty days after the dissolution.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In accordance with the Constitution of Ireland, parliamentary elections must be held at least every seven years, though a lower limit may be set by statute law.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The current government is a coalition of Fianna Fáil, Fine Gael, and some independents with Micheál Martin of Fianna Fáil as Taoiseach and Simon Harris of Fine Gael as Tánaiste.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Opposition parties in the current Dáil are Sinn Féin, the Labour Party, People Before Profit–Solidarity, Social Democrats, Aontú, The Green Party as well as a number of independents.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland has been a member state of the European Union since 1973.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Citizens of the United Kingdom can freely enter the country without a passport due to the Common Travel Area, which is a passport-free zone comprising the islands of Ireland, Great Britain, the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] However, some identification is required at airports and seaports.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Regimes of the World index classified Ireland as a liberal democracy in year 2024.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Corruption in the Republic of Ireland includes clientelism and pork barrel politics.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Local Government (Ireland) Act 1898 was the founding statute of the present system of local government, while the Twentieth Amendment to the constitution of 1999 provided for its constitutional recognition.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The twenty-six traditional counties of Ireland are the basis of the local government areas, with the traditional counties of Cork, Dublin and Galway containing two or more local government areas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Local Government Act 2001, as amended by the Local Government Reform Act 2014, provides for a system of thirty-one local authorities – twenty-six county councils, two city and county councils, and three city councils.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Counties (with the exception of the three counties in Dublin) are divided into municipal districts.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] A second local government tier of town councils was abolished in 2014.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Local authorities are responsible for matters such as planning, local roads, sanitation, and libraries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The breaching of county boundaries should be avoided as far as practicable in drawing Dáil constituencies.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Counties with greater populations have multiple constituencies, some of more than one county, but generally do not cross county boundaries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The counties are grouped into three regions, each with a Regional Assembly composed of members delegated by the various county and city councils in the region.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The regions do not have any direct administrative role as such, but they serve for planning, coordination and statistical purposes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland has a common law legal system with a written constitution that provides for a parliamentary democracy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The court system consists of the Supreme Court, the Court of Appeal, the High Court, the Circuit Court and the District Court, all of which apply the Irish law and hear both civil and criminal matters.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Trials for serious offences must usually be held before a jury.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The High Court, Court of Appeal and the Supreme Court have authority, by means of judicial review, to determine the compatibility of laws and activities of other institutions of the state with the constitution and the law.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Except in exceptional circumstances, court hearings must occur in public.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Garda Síochána (*lit.* Guardians of the Peace), more commonly referred to as the Gardaí, is the state's civilian police force.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The force is responsible for all aspects of civil policing, both in terms of territory and infrastructure.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It is headed by the Garda Commissioner, who is appointed by the Government.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Most uniformed members do not routinely carry firearms.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Standard policing is traditionally carried out by uniformed officers equipped only with a baton and pepper spray.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Military Police is the corps of the Irish Army responsible for the provision of policing service personnel and providing a military police presence to forces while on exercise and deployment.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In wartime, additional tasks include the provision of a traffic control organisation to allow rapid movement of military formations to their mission areas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Other wartime roles include control of prisoners of war and refugees.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's citizenship laws relate to "the island of Ireland", including islands and seas, thereby extending them to Northern Ireland, which is part of the United Kingdom.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2024, Ireland was second only to Iceland in the list of the world's most peaceful countries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Foreign relations are substantially influenced by membership of the European Union, although bilateral relations with the United Kingdom and United States are also important.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It held the Presidency of the Council of the European Union on six occasions, most recently from January to June 2013.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland tends towards independence in foreign policy; thus the country is not a member of NATO and has a longstanding policy of military neutrality.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This policy has led to the Irish Defence Forces contributing to peace-keeping missions with the United Nations since 1960, including during the Congo Crisis and subsequently in Cyprus, Lebanon and Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Despite Irish neutrality during World War II, Ireland had more than 50,000 participants in the war through enlistment in the British armed forces.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] During the Cold War, Irish military policy, while ostensibly neutral, was biased towards NATO.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] During the Cuban Missile Crisis, Seán Lemass authorised the search of Cuban and Czechoslovak aircraft passing through Shannon and passed the information to the CIA.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's air facilities were used by the United States military for the delivery of military personnel involved in the 2003 invasion of Iraq through Shannon Airport.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The airport had previously been used for the United States invasion of Afghanistan in 2001, as well as the First Gulf War.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Since 1999, Ireland has been a member of NATO's Partnership for Peace (PfP) program and NATO's Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC), which is aimed at creating trust between NATO and other states in Europe and the former Soviet Union.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland is a neutral country, and has "triple-lock" rules governing the participation of Irish troops in conflict zones, whereby approval must be given by the UN, the Dáil and Government.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Accordingly, its military role is limited to national self-defence and participation in United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Defence Forces (*Óglaigh na hÉireann*) are made up of the Army, Naval Service, Air Corps and Reserve Defence Force.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] It is small but well equipped, with almost 10,000 full-time military personnel and over 2,000 in reserve.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Daily deployments of the Defence Forces cover aid to civil power operations, protection and patrol of Irish territorial waters and EEZ by the Irish Naval Service, and UN, EU and PfP peace-keeping missions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] By 1996, over 40,000 Irish service personnel had served in international UN peacekeeping missions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Air Corps is the air component of the Defence Forces and operates sixteen fixed wing aircraft and eight helicopters.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Irish Naval Service is Ireland's navy, and operates six patrol ships, and smaller numbers of inflatable boats and training vessels, and has armed boarding parties capable of seizing a ship and a special unit of frogmen.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The military includes the Reserve Defence Forces (Army Reserve and Naval Service Reserve) for part-time reservists.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's special forces include the Army Ranger Wing, which trains and operates with international special operations units.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The President is the formal Supreme Commander of the Defence Forces, but in practice these Forces answer to the Government via the Minister for Defence.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2017, Ireland signed the United Nations Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland is an open economy and ranks first for "high-value" foreign direct investment (FDI) flows.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland ranks 5th of 187 (IMF) and 6th of 175 (World Bank) in GDP per capita as well as ranking in the top ten for GNI per capita.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This is particularly relevant in Ireland's economy, as GDP disproportionately includes income from non-Irish owned companies, which often flows out of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Foreign multinationals are the main driver of Ireland's economy, employing a quarter of the private sector workforce, and paying 80% of Irish corporate taxes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] 14 of Ireland's top 20 firms (by 2017 turnover) are US-based multinationals and 80% of foreign multinationals in Ireland are from the US.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland adopted the euro currency in 2002 along with eleven other EU member states.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Following the Great Recession and the bursting of the Irish property bubble, the country officially exited recession in 2010, driven by a growth in exports from US multinationals in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] However, due to a rise in the cost of public borrowing due to government guarantees of private banking debt, the Irish government accepted an €85 billion programme of assistance from the EU, International Monetary Fund (IMF) and bilateral loans from the United Kingdom, Sweden and Denmark.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Following three years of contraction, the economy grew by 0.7% in 2011 and 0.9% in 2012.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The median equivalised disposable income was $31,392 (PPP) per year in 2021.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The unemployment rate was 14.7% in 2012, including 18.5% among recent immigrants.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In March 2016 the unemployment rate was reported by the CSO to be 8.6%, down from a peak unemployment rate of 15.1% in February 2012.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In addition to unemployment, net emigration from Ireland between 2008 and 2013 totalled 120,100, or some 2.6% of the total population according to the Census of Ireland 2011.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] One-third of the emigrants were aged between 15 and 24.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] By November 2022, unemployment had fallen back to 4.4%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland exited its EU-IMF bailout programme on 15 December 2013.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Having implemented budget cuts, reforms and sold assets, Ireland was again able to access debt markets.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Since then, Ireland has been able to sell long term bonds at record rates.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] However, the stabilisation of the Irish credit bubble required a large transfer of debt from the private sector balance sheet (highest OECD leverage), to the public sector balance sheet (almost unleveraged, pre-crisis), via Irish bank bailouts and public deficit spending.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The transfer of this debt means that Ireland, in 2017, still has one of the highest levels of both public sector indebtedness, and private sector indebtedness, in the EU-28/OECD.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland became one of the main destinations for US pharmaceutical corporate tax inversions from 2009 to 2016.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The country has also become the largest foreign location for large US technology multinationals (i.e.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Apple, Google, Microsoft, Facebook), which delivered a GDP growth rate of 26.3% (and GNP growth rate of 18.7%) in 2015.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This growth was subsequently shown to be due to Apple restructuring its "double Irish" subsidiary (Apple Sales International, currently under threat of a €13bn EU "illegal state aid" fine for preferential tax treatment).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The transformation of Ireland's tax policy started with the creation of a 10% low-tax special economic zone, called the International Financial Services Centre (IFSC), in 1987.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2003, the IFSC was expanded nationwide with the reduction of Irish corporation tax from 32% to 12.5%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The multinational tax planning schemes corporations use in Ireland have materially affected Irish economic statistics.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] This reached a climax with what Paul Krugman termed leprechaun economics with double digit GDP growth rates in 2015 relating largely to Apple restructuring its Irish subsidiaries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Central Bank of Ireland introduced additional statistics based on a modified gross national income, to remove these distortions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] From the creation of the IFSC, the country experienced strong and sustained economic growth which fuelled a dramatic rise in Irish consumer borrowing and spending, and Irish construction and investment, which became known as the Celtic Tiger period.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] By 2007, Ireland had the highest private sector debt in the OECD with a household debt-to-disposable income ratio of 190%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Global capital markets, which had financed Ireland's build-up of debt in the Celtic Tiger period by enabling Irish banks to borrow in excess of the domestic deposit base to over 180% at peak, withdrew support in the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Their withdrawal from the over-borrowed Irish credit system would precipitate a deep Irish property correction which then led to the Post-2008 Irish banking crisis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The country's successful low-tax economy opens it to accusations of Ireland being a corporate haven.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] A 2017 study ranks Ireland as the 5th largest global Conduit OFC, which legally route funds to tax havens.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The EU's 2018 Digital Sales Tax (DST) and the desire for a Common Consolidated Corporate Tax Base was seen partially as an attempt to restrict "multinational tax schemes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Although multinational corporations dominate Ireland's export sector, exports from other sources also contribute significantly to the national income and particularly to employment and local economies outside of the major cities.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The activities of multinational companies based in Ireland have made it one of the largest exporters of pharmaceutical agents, medical devices and software-related goods and services in the world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's exports also relate to the activities of large Irish companies (such as Ryanair, Kerry Group, Smurfit Kappa) and increasingly Irish based aircraft lessors such as Avolon.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The country exports mineral resources including zinc and lead concentrates and also has significant deposits of gypsum and smaller quantities of copper, aluminium oxide, silver, gold, barite, and dolomite.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Tourism in Ireland contributes about 4% of GDP and is a significant source of employment.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Other goods exports include agri-food such as cattle, beef, sheep and dairy products.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ireland's major imports include data processing equipment, chemicals, petroleum and petroleum products, textiles, and clothing.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Financial services provided by multinational corporations based at the Irish Financial Services Centre also contribute to Irish exports.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The EU is by far the country's largest trading partner, accounting for 57.9% of exports and 60.7% of imports.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Prior to Brexit, the United Kingdom was the most important trading partner within the EU, accounting for 15.4% of exports and 32.1% of imports.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Outside the EU, the United States accounted for 23.2% of exports and 14.1% of imports in 2010.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] ESB, Bord Gáis Energy and Airtricity are the three main electricity and gas suppliers in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] There are 19.82 billion cubic metres of proven reserves of gas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Natural gas extraction previously occurred at the Kinsale Head until its exhaustion.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Corrib gas field was due to come on stream in 2013/14.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2012, the Barryroe field was confirmed to have up to 1.6 billion barrels of oil in reserve, with between 160 and 600 million recoverable.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] That could provide for Ireland's entire energy needs for up to 13 years, when it is developed in 2015/16.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] There have been significant efforts to increase the use of renewable and sustainable forms of energy in Ireland, particularly in wind power, with 3,000 MegaWatts of wind farms being constructed, some for the purpose of export.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Sustainable Energy Authority of Ireland (SEAI) has estimated that 6.5% of Ireland's 2011 energy requirements were produced by renewable sources.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The SEAI has also reported an increase in energy efficiency in Ireland with a 28% reduction in carbon emissions per house from 2005 to 2013.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2021, Ireland was the 24th largest wind energy producer in the world and the 3rd ranked in 2020 on a per capita basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The country's three main international airports at Dublin, Shannon and Cork serve many European and intercontinental routes with scheduled and chartered flights.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The London to Dublin air route is the ninth busiest international air route in the world, and also the busiest international air route in Europe, with 14,500 flights between the two in 2017.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] In 2015, 4.5 million people took the route, at that time, the world's second-busiest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Aer Lingus is the flag carrier of Ireland, although Ryanair is the country's largest airline.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Ryanair is Europe's largest low-cost carrier, the second largest in terms of passenger numbers, and the world's largest in terms of international passenger numbers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Railway services are provided by Iarnród Éireann (Irish Rail), which operates all internal intercity, commuter and freight railway services in the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Dublin is the centre of the network with two main stations, Heuston station and Connolly station, linking to the country's cities and main towns.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Enterprise service, which runs jointly with Northern Ireland Railways, connects Dublin and Belfast.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The whole of Ireland's mainline network operates on track with a gauge of 5 ft 3 in (1,600 mm), which is unique in Europe and has resulted in distinct rolling stock designs.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Dublin's public transport network includes the DART, Luas, Dublin Bus, and dublinbikes.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Motorways, national primary roads and national secondary roads are managed by Transport Infrastructure Ireland, while regional roads and local roads are managed by the local authorities in each of their respective areas.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The road network is primarily focused on the capital, but motorways connect it to other major Irish cities including Cork, Limerick, Waterford and Galway.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] Dublin is served by major infrastructure such as the East-Link and West-Link toll-bridges, as well as the Dublin Port Tunnel.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p01] The Jack Lynch Tunnel, under the River Lee in Cork, and the Limerick Tunnel, under the River Shannon, were two major projects outside Dublin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Genetic research suggests that the earliest settlers migrated from Iberia following the most recent ice age.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] After the Mesolithic, Neolithic and Bronze Age, migrants introduced a Celtic language and culture.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Migrants from the two latter eras still represent the genetic heritage of most Irish people.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Gaelic tradition expanded and became the dominant form over time.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish people are a combination of Gaelic, Norse, Anglo-Norman, French, and British ancestry.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The population of Ireland was recorded as 5,149,139 in 2022, an increase of 8% since 2016.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2011, Ireland had the highest birth rate in the European Union (16 births per 1,000 of population).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2014, 36.3% of births were to unmarried women.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Annual population growth rates exceeded 2% during the 2002–2006 intercensal period, which was attributed to high rates of natural increase and immigration.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] This rate declined somewhat during the subsequent 2006–2011 intercensal period, with an average annual percentage change of 1.6%.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) in 2017 was estimated at 1.80 children born per woman, below the replacement rate of 2.1, it remains considerably below the high of 4.2 children born per woman in 1850.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2018 the median age of the Irish population was 37.1 years.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] At the time of the 2022 census, the number of non-Irish nationals was recorded at 631,785.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] This represents an 8% increase from the 2016 census figure of 535,475.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish Constitution describes Irish as the "national language" and the "first official language", but English, the "second official language", dominates.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In the 2016 census, about 1.75 million people (40% of the population) said they were able to speak Irish but, of those, under 74,000 spoke it on a daily basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish is spoken as a community language only in a small number of rural areas mostly in the west and south of the country, collectively known as the Gaeltacht.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Except in Gaeltacht regions, road signs are usually bilingual.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Most public notices and print media are in English only.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] While the state is officially bilingual, citizens can often struggle to access state services in Irish and most government publications are not available in both languages, even though citizens have the right to deal with the state in Irish.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish language media include the TV channel TG4, the radio station RTÉ Raidió na Gaeltachta and online newspaper Tuairisc.ie.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In the Irish Defence Forces, all foot and arms drill commands are given in the Irish language.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] As a result of immigration, Polish is the most widely spoken language in Ireland after English, with Irish as the third most spoken.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Several other Central European languages (namely Czech, Hungarian and Slovak), as well as Baltic languages (Lithuanian and Latvian) are also spoken on a day-to-day basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other languages spoken in Ireland include Shelta, spoken by Irish Travellers, and a dialect of Scots is spoken by some Ulster Scots people in Donegal.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Most secondary school students choose to learn one or two foreign languages.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Languages available for the Junior Certificate and the Leaving Certificate include French, German, Italian and Spanish; Leaving Certificate students can also study Arabic, Japanese and Russian.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Some secondary schools also offer Ancient Greek, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The study of Irish is generally compulsory for Leaving Certificate students, but some may qualify for an exemption in some circumstances, such as learning difficulties or entering the country after age 11.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Religious freedom is constitutionally provided for in Ireland, and the country's constitution has been secular since 1973.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Christianity is the predominant religion, and while Ireland remains a predominantly Catholic country, the percentage of the population who identified as Catholic on the census has declined significantly in the early 21st century, from 84.2 percent in the 2011 census to 69.1 percent in 2022.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other results from the 2016 census were: 4.2% Protestant, 1.3% Orthodox, 1.3% Muslim, and 9.8% having no religion.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] According to a Georgetown University study, before 2000 the country had one of the highest rates of regular mass attendance in the Western world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] While daily attendance was 13% in 2006, there was a reduction in weekly attendance from 81% in 1990 to 48% in 2006; the decline was reported as stabilising, though.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2011, it was reported that weekly mass attendance in Dublin was 18% and even lower among younger generations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Church of Ireland, adhered to by 2.7% of the population, is the second largest Christian denomination.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Membership declined throughout the twentieth century but experienced an increase early in the 21st century alongside other Christian denominations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other significant Protestant denominations are the Presbyterian Church and Methodist Church.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Immigration has contributed to a growth in Hindu and Muslim populations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In percentage terms, as of the 2006 census, Orthodox Christianity and Islam were the fastest growing religions with increases of 100% and 70% respectively.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland's patron saints are Patrick, Bridget, and Columba; Saint Patrick is commonly recognised as the primary patron saint.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Saint Patrick's Day is celebrated on 17 March in Ireland and abroad as the Irish national day with parades and other celebrations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] As with other traditionally Catholic European states, such as Spain and Italy, Ireland underwent a period of legal secularisation in the late twentieth century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 1972, the article of the Constitution naming specific religious groups was deleted by the Fifth Amendment in a referendum.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Article 44 remains in the Constitution: "The State acknowledges that the homage of public worship is due to Almighty God.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Although most schools in Ireland are patronised by religious organisations, government policy has been to "transfer" some schools to non-denominational or multi-denominational patronage, and a secularist trend is occurring among younger generations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has three levels of education: primary, secondary and higher education.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The education systems are largely under the direction of the Government via the Minister for Education.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Recognised primary and secondary schools must adhere to the curriculum established by the relevant authorities.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Education is compulsory between the ages of six and fifteen years, and all children up to the age of eighteen must complete the first three years of secondary, including one sitting of the Junior Certificate examination.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] There are approximately 3,300 primary schools in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The vast majority (92%) are under the patronage of the Catholic Church.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Schools run by religious organisations, but receiving public money and recognition, cannot discriminate against pupils based upon religion or lack thereof.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A sanctioned system of preference does exist, where students of a particular religion may be accepted before those who do not share the ethos of the school, in a case where a school's quota has already been reached.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Leaving Certificate, which is taken after two years of study, is the final examination in the secondary school system.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Those intending to pursue higher education normally take this examination, with access to third-level courses generally depending on results obtained from the best six subjects taken, on a competitive basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Third-level education awards are conferred by at least 38 Higher Education Institutions – this includes the constituent or linked colleges of seven universities, plus other designated institutions of the Higher Education and Training Awards Council.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] According to the 2022 US News rankings, Ireland is among the top twenty best countries for education.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Programme for International Student Assessment, coordinated by the OECD, currently ranks Ireland as having the fourth highest reading score, ninth highest science score and thirteenth highest mathematics score, among OECD countries, in its 2012 assessment.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2012, Irish students aged 15 years had the second highest levels of reading literacy in the EU.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland also has 0.747 of the World's top 500 Universities per capita, which ranks the country in 8th place in the world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Primary, secondary and higher (university/college) level education are all free in Ireland for all EU citizens.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] There are charges to cover student services and examinations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In addition, 37 percent of Ireland's population has a university or college degree, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Healthcare in Ireland is provided by both public and private healthcare providers.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Minister for Health has responsibility for setting overall health service policy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Every resident of Ireland is entitled to receive health care through the public health care system, which is managed by the Health Service Executive and funded by general taxation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A person may be required to pay a subsidised fee for certain health care received; this depends on income, age, illness or disability.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] All maternity services are provided free of charge and children up to the age of 6 months.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Emergency care is provided to patients who present to a hospital emergency department.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] However, visitors to emergency departments in non-emergency situations who are not referred by their GP may incur a fee of €100.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In some circumstances this fee is not payable or may be waived.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Anyone holding a European Health Insurance Card is entitled to free maintenance and treatment in public beds in Health Service Executive and voluntary hospitals.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Outpatient services are also provided for free.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] However, the majority of patients on median incomes or above are required to pay subsidised hospital charges.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Private health insurance is available to the population for those who want to avail of it.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The average life expectancy in Ireland in 2021 was 82.4 years (OECD list), with 80.5 years for men and 84.3 years for women.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It has the highest birth rate in the EU (16.8 births per 1,000 inhabitants, compared to an EU average of 10.7) and a very low infant mortality rate (3.5 per 1,000 live births).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish healthcare system ranked 13th out of 34 European countries in 2012 according to the European Health Consumer Index produced by Health Consumer Powerhouse.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The same report ranked the Irish healthcare system as having the 8th best health outcomes but only the 21st most accessible system in Europe.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland's culture was for centuries predominantly Gaelic, and it remains one of the six principal Celtic nations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Following the Anglo-Norman invasion in the 12th century, and gradual British conquest and colonisation beginning in the 16th century, Ireland became influenced by English and Scottish culture.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Subsequently, Irish culture, though distinct in many aspects, shares characteristics with the rest of the Anglosphere, Catholic Europe, and other Celtic regions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish diaspora, one of the world's largest and most dispersed, has contributed to the globalisation of Irish culture, producing many prominent figures in art, music, and science.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has made a significant contribution to world literature in both the English and Irish languages.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Modern Irish fiction began with the publishing of the 1726 novel *Gulliver's Travels* by Jonathan Swift.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other writers of importance during the 18th century and their most notable works include Laurence Sterne with the publication of *The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman* and Oliver Goldsmith's *The Vicar of Wakefield*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Numerous Irish novelists emerged during the 19th century, including Maria Edgeworth, John Banim, Gerald Griffin, Charles Kickham, William Carleton, George Moore, and Somerville and Ross.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Bram Stoker is best known as the author of the 1897 novel *Dracula*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] James Joyce (1882–1941) published his most famous work *Ulysses* in 1922, which is an interpretation of the *Odyssey* set in Dublin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Edith Somerville continued writing after the death of her partner Martin Ross in 1915.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Smithson was one of several authors catering for fans of romantic fiction in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] After the Second World War, popular novels were published by, among others, Brian O'Nolan, who published as Flann O'Brien, Elizabeth Bowen, and Kate O'Brien.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] During the final decades of the 20th century, Edna O'Brien, John McGahern, Maeve Binchy, Joseph O'Connor, Roddy Doyle, Colm Tóibín, and John Banville came to the fore as novelists.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Patricia Lynch was a prolific children's author in the 20th century, while Eoin Colfer's works were NYT Best Sellers in this genre in the early 21st century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In the genre of the short story, which is a form favoured by many Irish writers, the most prominent figures include Seán Ó Faoláin, Frank O'Connor and William Trevor.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Well known Irish poets include Patrick Kavanagh, Thomas McCarthy, Dermot Bolger, and Nobel Prize in Literature laureates William Butler Yeats and Seamus Heaney (born in Northern Ireland but resided in Dublin).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Prominent writers in the Irish language are Pádraic Ó Conaire, Máirtín Ó Cadhain, Séamus Ó Grianna, and Nuala Ní Dhomhnaill.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The history of Irish theatre begins with the expansion of the English administration in Dublin during the early 17th century, and since then, Ireland has significantly contributed to English drama.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In its early history, theatrical productions in Ireland tended to serve political purposes, but as more theatres opened and the popular audience grew, a more diverse range of entertainments were staged.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Many Dublin-based theatres developed links with their London equivalents, and British productions frequently found their way to the Irish stage.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] However, most Irish playwrights went abroad to establish themselves.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In the 18th century, Oliver Goldsmith and Richard Brinsley Sheridan were two of the most successful playwrights on the London stage at that time.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other Irish playwrights of the 20th century include Denis Johnston, Thomas Kilroy, Tom Murphy, Hugh Leonard, Frank McGuinness, and John B.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish traditional music has remained vibrant, despite globalising cultural forces, and retains many traditional aspects.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It has influenced various music genres, such as American country and roots music, and to some extent modern rock.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It has occasionally been blended with styles such as rock and roll and punk rock.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has also produced many internationally known artists in other genres, such as rock, pop, jazz, and blues.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland's best selling musical act is the rock band U2, who have sold 170 million copies of their albums worldwide since their formation in 1976.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] There are a number of classical music ensembles around the country, such as the RTÉ Performing Groups.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland also has two opera organisations: Irish National Opera in Dublin, and the annual Wexford Opera Festival, which promotes lesser-known operas, takes place during October and November.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has participated in the Eurovision Song Contest since 1965.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Its first win was in 1970, when Dana won with *All Kinds of Everything*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It has subsequently won the competition six more times, the highest number of wins by any competing country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The phenomenon *Riverdance* originated as an interval performance during the 1994 contest.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish dance can broadly be divided into social dance and performance dance.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish social dance can be divided into *céilí* and set dancing.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish set dances are quadrilles, danced by 4 couples arranged in a square, while céilí dances are danced by varied formations of couples of 2 to 16 people.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] There are also many stylistic differences between these two forms.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish social dance is a living tradition, and variations in particular dances are found across the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In some places dances are deliberately modified and new dances are choreographed.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Performance dance is traditionally referred to as stepdance.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish stepdance, popularised by the show *Riverdance*, is notable for its rapid leg movements, with the body and arms being kept largely stationary.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The solo stepdance is generally characterised by a controlled but not rigid upper body, straight arms, and quick, precise movements of the feet.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The solo dances can either be in "soft shoe" or "hard shoe".
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has a wealth of structures, surviving from the Neolithic period, such as *Brú na Bóinne*, Poulnabrone dolmen, Castlestrange stone, Turoe stone, and Drombeg stone circle.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] As Ireland was never a part of the Roman Empire, ancient architecture in Greco-Roman style is non-existent, in contrast to most of Western Europe.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The country instead had an extended period of Iron Age architecture.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish round tower originated during the Early Medieval period and several of these structure are still extant throughout the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Christianity introduced simple monastic houses, such as Clonmacnoise, Skellig Michael and Scattery Island.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A stylistic similarity has been remarked between these double monasteries and those of the Copts of Egypt.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Gaelic kings and aristocrats occupied ringforts or *crannógs*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Church reforms during the 12th century via the Cistercians stimulated further continental influence, with the Romanesque styled Mellifont, Boyle and Tintern abbeys.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Gaelic settlement had been limited to the Monastic proto-towns, such as Kells, where the current street pattern preserves the original circular settlement outline to some extent.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Significant urban settlements only developed following the period of Viking invasions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The major Hiberno-Norse Longphorts were located on the coast, but with minor inland fluvial settlements, such as the eponymous Longford.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Castles were built by the Anglo-Normans during the late 12th century, such as Dublin Castle and Kilkenny Castle, and the concept of the planned walled trading town was introduced, which gained legal status and several rights by grant of a Charter under Feudalism.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] These charters specifically governed the design of these towns.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Two significant waves of planned town formation followed, the first being the 16th- and 17th-century plantation towns, which were used as a mechanism for the Tudor English kings to suppress local insurgency, followed by 18th-century landlord towns.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Surviving Norman founded planned towns include Drogheda and Youghal; plantation towns include Portlaoise and Portarlington; well-preserved 18th-century planned towns include Westport and Ballinasloe.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] These episodes of planned settlement account for many of the present-day towns throughout the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Gothic cathedrals, such as St Patrick's, were also introduced by the Normans.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Franciscans were dominant in directing the abbeys by the Late Middle Ages, while elegant tower houses, such as Bunratty Castle, were built by the Gaelic and Norman aristocracy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Many religious buildings were ruined with the dissolution of the monasteries.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] With the erection of buildings such as The Custom House, Four Courts, General Post Office and King's Inns, the neoclassical and Georgian styles flourished, especially in Dublin.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Georgian townhouses produced streets of singular distinction, particularly in Dublin, Limerick and Cork.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Following Catholic emancipation, cathedrals and churches influenced by the French Gothic Revival emerged, such as St Colman's and St Finbarre's.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has long been associated with vernacular thatched roof cottages, though these are nowadays in decline.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Beginning with the American designed art deco church at Turner's Cross, Cork in 1927, Irish architecture followed the international trend towards modern and sleek building styles since the 20th century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other developments include the regeneration of Ballymun and an urban extension of Dublin at Adamstown.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Since the establishment of the Dublin Docklands Development Authority in 1997, the Dublin Docklands area underwent large-scale redevelopment, which included the construction of the Convention Centre Dublin and Grand Canal Theatre.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Completed in 2018, Capital Dock in Dublin is the tallest building in the Republic of Ireland achieving 79 metres (259 feet) in height (the Obel Tower in Belfast, Northern Ireland being the tallest in Ireland).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Royal Institute of the Architects of Ireland regulates the practice of architecture in the state.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ) is Ireland's public service broadcaster, funded by a television licence fee and advertising.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] RTÉ operates two national television channels, RTÉ One and RTÉ Two.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The other independent national television channels are Virgin Media One, Virgin Media Two, Virgin Media Three, Virgin Media Four and TG4, the latter of which is a public service broadcaster for speakers of the Irish language.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] All these channels are available on Saorview, the national free-to-air digital terrestrial television service.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Additional channels included in the service are RTÉ News, RTÉjr, and RTÉ One +1.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Subscription-based television providers operating in Ireland include Virgin Media and Sky.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The BBC's Northern Irish division is widely available in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] BBC One Northern Ireland and BBC Two Northern Ireland are available in pay television providers including Virgin and Sky as well as via signal overspill by Freeview in border counties.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Supported by the Irish Film Board, the Irish film industry grew significantly since the 1990s, with the promotion of indigenous films as well as the attraction of international productions like *Braveheart* and *Saving Private Ryan*.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A large number of regional and local radio stations are available countrywide.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A survey showed that a consistent 85% of adults listen to a mixture of national, regional and local stations on a daily basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] RTÉ Radio operates four national stations, Radio 1, 2fm, Lyric fm, and RnaG.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It also operates four national DAB radio stations.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] There are two independent national stations: Today FM and Newstalk.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Censorship in the Republic of Ireland is mainly managed by the Censorship of Publications Board, Coimisiún na Meán and Irish Film Classification Office.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has a traditionally competitive print media, which is divided into daily national newspapers and weekly regional newspapers, as well as national Sunday editions.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The strength of the British press is a unique feature of the Irish print media scene, with the availability of a wide selection of British published newspapers and magazines.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Eurostat reported that 82% of Irish households had Internet access in 2013 compared to the EU average of 79% but only 67% had broadband access.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish cuisine was traditionally based on meat and dairy products, supplemented with vegetables and seafood.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Examples of popular Irish cuisine include boxty, colcannon, coddle, stew, and bacon and cabbage.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland is known for the full Irish breakfast, which involves a fried or grilled meal generally consisting of rashers, egg, sausage, white and black pudding, and fried tomato.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Apart from the influence by European and international dishes, there has been an emergence of a new Irish cuisine based on traditional ingredients handled in new ways.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] This cuisine is based on fresh vegetables, fish, oysters, mussels and other shellfish, and the wide range of hand-made cheeses that are now being produced across the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Shellfish have increased in popularity, especially due to the high quality shellfish available from the country's coastline.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The most popular fish include salmon and cod.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Traditional breads include soda bread and wheaten bread.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Barmbrack is a yeasted bread with added sultanas and raisins, traditionally eaten on Halloween.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Popular everyday beverages among the Irish include tea and coffee.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Alcoholic drinks associated with Ireland include Poitín and the world-famous Guinness, which is a dry stout that originated in the brewery of Arthur Guinness at St.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Irish whiskey is also popular throughout the country and comes in various forms, including single malt, single grain, and blended whiskey.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Gaelic football and hurling are the traditional sports of Ireland as well as popular spectator sports.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] They are administered by the Gaelic Athletics Association on an all-Ireland basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other Gaelic games organised by the association include Gaelic handball and rounders.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Association football (soccer) is the third most popular spectator sport and has the highest level of participation.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Although the League of Ireland is the national league, the English Premier League is the most popular among the public.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Republic of Ireland national football team plays at international level and is administered by the Football Association of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish Rugby Football Union is the governing body of rugby union, which is played at local and international levels on an all-Ireland basis, and has produced players such as Brian O'Driscoll and Ronan O'Gara, who were on the team that won the Grand Slam in 2009.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The success of the Irish Cricket Team in the 2007 Cricket World Cup has led to an increase in the popularity of cricket, which is also administered on an all-Ireland basis by Cricket Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland are one of the twelve Test playing members of the International Cricket Council, having been granted Test status in 2017.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Professional domestic matches are played between the major cricket unions of Leinster, Munster, Northern, and North West.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Netball is represented by the Ireland national netball team.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Golf is another popular sport in Ireland, with over 300 courses countrywide.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The country has produced several internationally successful golfers, such as Pádraig Harrington, Shane Lowry and Paul McGinley.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Horse racing has a large presence, with influential breeding and racing operations in the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Racing takes place at courses at The Curragh Racecourse in County Kildare, Leopardstown Racecourse just outside Dublin, and Galway.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland has produced champion horses such as Galileo, Montjeu, and Sea the Stars.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Boxing is Ireland's most successful sport at an Olympic level.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Administered by the Irish Athletic Boxing Association on an all-Ireland basis, it has gained in popularity as a result of the international success of boxers such as Bernard Dunne, Andy Lee and Katie Taylor.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Some of Ireland's highest performers in athletics have competed at the Olympic Games, such as Eamonn Coghlan and Sonia O'Sullivan.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The annual Dublin Marathon and Dublin Women's Mini Marathon are two of the most popular athletics events in the country.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Rugby league is represented by the Ireland national rugby league team and administered by Rugby League Ireland (who are full member of the Rugby League European Federation) on an all-Ireland basis.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The team compete in the European Cup (rugby league) and the Rugby League World Cup.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland reached the quarter-finals of the 2000 Rugby League World Cup as well as reaching the semi-finals in the 2008 Rugby League World Cup.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Irish Elite League is a domestic competition for rugby league teams in Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] While Australian rules football in Ireland has a limited following, a series of International rules football games (constituting a hybrid of the Australian and Gaelic football codes) takes place annually between teams representing Ireland and Australia.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Baseball and basketball are also emerging sports in Ireland, both of which have an international team representing the island of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Other sports which retain a following in Ireland include cycling, greyhound racing, horse riding, and motorsport.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland ranks fifth in the world in terms of gender equality.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2011, Ireland was ranked the most charitable country in Europe, and second most charitable in the world.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Contraception was controlled in Ireland until 1979, however, the receding influence of the Catholic Church has led to an increasingly secularised society.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A constitutional ban on divorce was lifted following a referendum in 1995.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Divorce rates in Ireland are very low compared to European Union averages (0.7 divorced people per 1,000 population in 2011) while the marriage rate in Ireland is slightly above the European Union average (4.6 marriages per 1,000 population per year in 2012).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Abortion had been banned throughout the period of the Irish state, first through provisions of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 and later by the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Act 2013.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The right to life of the unborn was protected in the constitution by the Eighth Amendment in 1983; this provision was removed following a referendum, and replaced it with a provision allowing legislation to regulate the termination of pregnancy.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018 passed later that year provided for abortion generally during the first 12 weeks of pregnancy, and in specified circumstances after that date.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Capital punishment is constitutionally banned in Ireland, while discrimination based on age, gender, sexual orientation, marital or familial status, religion, race or membership of the travelling community is illegal.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The legislation which outlawed homosexual acts was repealed in 1993.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 permitted civil partnerships between same-sex couples.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The Children and Family Relationships Act 2015 allowed for adoption rights for couples other than married couples, including civil partners and cohabitants, and provided for donor-assisted human reproduction; however, significant sections of the Act have yet to be commenced.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Following a referendum held on 23 May 2015, Ireland became the eighteenth country to provide in law for same-sex marriage, and the first to do so by popular vote.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Ireland became the first country in the world to introduce an environmental levy for plastic shopping bags in 2002 and a public smoking ban in 2004.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Recycling in Ireland is carried out extensively, and Ireland has the second highest rate of packaging recycling in the European Union.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It was the first country in Europe to ban incandescent lightbulbs in 2008 and the first EU country to ban in-store tobacco advertising and product display in 2009.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] In 2015, Ireland became the second country in the world to introduce plain cigarette packaging.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Despite the above measures to discourage tobacco use, smoking rates in Ireland remain at approximately 15.4% as of 2020.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The state shares many symbols with the island of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] These include the colours green and blue, animals such as the Irish wolfhound and stags, structures such as round towers and celtic crosses, and designs such as Celtic knots and spirals.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The shamrock, a type of clover, has been a national symbol of Ireland since the 17th century when it became customary to wear it as a symbol on St.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] These symbols are used by state institutions as well as private bodies in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The flag of Ireland is a tricolour of green, white and orange.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The flag originates with the Young Ireland movement of the mid-19th century but was not popularised until its use during the Easter Rising of 1916.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The colours represent the Gaelic tradition (green) and the followers of William of Orange in Ireland (orange), with white representing the aspiration for peace between them.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It was adopted as the flag of the Irish Free State in 1922 and continues to be used as the sole flag and ensign of the state.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] A naval jack, a green flag with a yellow harp, is set out in Defence Forces Regulations and flown from the bows of warships in addition to the national flag in limited circumstances (e.g. when a ship is not underway).
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] It is based on the unofficial green ensign of Ireland used in the 18th and 19th centuries and the traditional green flag of Ireland dating from the 16th century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Like the national flag, the national anthem, *Amhrán na bhFiann* (English: A Soldier's Song), has its roots in the Easter Rising, when the song was sung by the rebels.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Although originally published in English in 1912, the song was translated into Irish in 1923 and the Irish-language version is more commonly sung today.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The song was officially adopted as the anthem of the Irish Free State in 1926 and continues as the national anthem of the state.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The first four bars of the chorus followed by the last five comprise the presidential salute.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The arms of Ireland originate as the arms of the monarchs of Ireland and was recorded as the arms of the King of Ireland in the 12th century.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] From the union of the crowns of England, Scotland and Ireland in 1603, they have appeared quartered on the royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] Today, they are the personal arms of the president of Ireland whilst he or she is in office and are flown as the presidential standard.
[src:republic-of-ireland/republic-of-ireland-p02] The harp symbol is used extensively by the state to mark official documents, Irish coinage and on the seal of the president of Ireland.
